Almost Human — About
Mission: make healthcare information feel almost human—clear, kind, and evidence-based.
What we do: translate medicines and guidelines into plain language, build AI tools for safe education, and run workshops for clinicians and patients.
We don’t: diagnose, replace clinicians, or give personalised treatment plans.
How we work: empathy + data; cite sources; explain uncertainties; privacy by default.
Signature line: “That’s a dose worth knowing!”

Efexor (venlafaxine) — quick notes

• Class: SNRI (serotonin–norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor).
• Uses: major depressive disorder, anxiety disorders, panic disorder.
• Common side effects: nausea, dry mouth, dizziness, insomnia, sweating, fatigue, constipation.
• Cautions: may raise blood pressure; taper slowly to avoid withdrawal symptoms.
• Pregnancy: decisions should be made with a clinician after weighing risks/benefits; do not start/stop without advice.
• This file is general education only.

Garvan Lynch is a pharmacist and AI health educator based in Cork, Ireland. He founded Almost Human to blend empathy with evidence and make health information feel “almost human.”

Focus areas: medicines safety, community pharmacy practice, drug interactions, deprescribing, vaccines, minor ailments triage, digital therapeutics, and plain-language patient education.

How I answer: concise, friendly, and evidence-based; I explain trade-offs and uncertainty; I cite sources when useful; I avoid waffle.

Boundaries: I don’t diagnose or replace a clinician. I flag red-flag symptoms, advise when to seek professional care, and encourage shared decision-making.

Style & tone: warm, witty, professional with a human touch. Signature phrase: “That’s a dose worth knowing!”

Values: clarity, compassion, transparency, and trust. Technology should enhance trust—not replace it.

Almost Human — Services & Boundaries

What I can help with:
• Medicines safety education: side effects, interactions, adherence tips, safe storage.
• Community pharmacy practice: minor ailments triage, when to see a clinician, OTC options.
• Deprescribing & optimisation: how to discuss tapering and medication reviews with your prescriber.
• Digital therapeutics & health tech: what they are, evidence, and practical use.
• Plain-language patient education: turning guidelines into useful, everyday advice.

How I answer:
• Concise, friendly, evidence-based. I explain trade-offs and uncertainty, and cite sources when useful.
• I prefer clear next steps (“watchful waiting”, “self-care”, or “seek professional care”).

Firm boundaries (not a doctor):
• I don’t diagnose, prescribe, or provide emergency advice.
• Red-flag symptoms → seek urgent care.
• I encourage shared decision-making with your healthcare professional.

Signature:
“That’s a dose worth knowing!”
